---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import "../styles/pages/glossary.css";
---

<Layout
  title="Glossary | Liberation and Inclusion Translation"
  description="A trauma-informed glossary explaining how key biblical terms are translated in the Liberation and Inclusion Translation (LIT), with historical, linguistic, and theological context."
  canonical="https://litbible.net/glossary/"
  bg="white"
  type="glossary"
>
  <div class="glossary-page">
    <!-- PAGE HEADER (white background) -->
    <section class="glossary-hero" aria-labelledby="glossary-title">
      <div class="wrap">
        <h1 id="glossary-title" class="glossary-title">Glossary</h1>

        <p data-pagefind-ignore>
          There's a lot of words you would expect to see if you're familiar with
          the Bible that you won't see in this translation. There's also a lot
          that may be unfamiliar. Some of them have been replaced because
          English has evolved over the last few hundred years and other words
          better capture the intended meaning of the Greek than what has become
          tradition. Others have been replaced because I'm convinced the words
          we've gotten used to were more or less the wrong choice to begin with.
          Other words have been replaced not because they are wrong but because
          we've gotten so used to them that it becomes difficult to be curious
          enough to really dig into what they are saying. There are footnotes
          throughout the translation explaining some of the differences you
          might find and why I chose the alternatives, but here's a concise
          guide all in one place for some of the changes. In bold, you'll find
          the traditional word. In italics is the Greek behind it. Underlined,
          you'll see what I've used in its place most often (it can change based
          on context). Feel free to contact me{" "}
          <a class="inline-link" href="/contact">here</a>{" "}
          if you think I've missed any important ones!
        </p>

        <!-- Sticky Glossary Menu (About-TOC style wrapper) -->
        <div
          class="glossary-toc"
          data-glossary-toc
          aria-label="Glossary Selection Menu"
          data-pagefind-ignore
        >
          <div class="glossary-toc__inner">
            <div class="glossary-toc__bar">
              <p class="glossary-toc__label">Jump to an entry</p>

              <button
                class="glossary-toc__toggle"
                type="button"
                aria-expanded="false"
                aria-controls="glossary-toc-tray"
              >
                <span class="glossary-toc__icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
                <span class="sr-only">Toggle glossary menu</span>
              </button>
            </div>

            <div class="glossary-toc__tray" id="glossary-toc-tray">
              <!-- MENU (mirrors Home page read-menu centering + mobile stack) -->
              <div class="title-menu" aria-label="Glossary Selection Menu">
                <div class="read-menu-wrap">
                  <div class="read-menu glossary-menu">
                    <label class="sr-only" for="category-select">
                      Select Glossary Category
                    </label>

                    <select
                      id="category-select"
                      aria-label="Select Glossary Category"
                    >
                      <option value="">Select Glossary Category</option>
                      <option value="traditional"
                        >Traditional Translation</option
                      >
                      <option value="lit">LIT Word Choice</option>
                    </select>

                    <label class="sr-only" for="word-select"
                      >Select a Word</label
                    >

                    <select
                      id="word-select"
                      aria-label="Select a Word"
                      disabled
                    >
                      <option value="">Select a Word</option>
                    </select>

                    <button id="go-button" type="button" disabled>Go</button>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Sticky toggle JS -->
        <script type="module">
          document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", () => {
            const toc = document.querySelector("[data-glossary-toc]");
            if (!toc) return;

            const btn = toc.querySelector(".glossary-toc__toggle");
            const tray = toc.querySelector(".glossary-toc__tray");
            if (!btn || !tray) return;

            const setOpen = (open) => {
              toc.classList.toggle("is-open", open);
              btn.setAttribute("aria-expanded", open ? "true" : "false");
            };

            const syncForViewport = () => {
              const isMobile = window.matchMedia("(max-width: 760px)").matches;
              setOpen(!isMobile);
            };

            syncForViewport();
            window.addEventListener("resize", syncForViewport);

            btn.addEventListener("click", () => {
              setOpen(!toc.classList.contains("is-open"));
            });

            // Close after selection on mobile (optional, nice UX)
            toc.addEventListener("change", () => {
              if (window.matchMedia("(max-width: 760px)").matches)
                setOpen(false);
            });
          });
        </script>

        <!-- Menu JS (your existing behavior) -->
        <script type="module">
          document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", () => {
            const glossary = {
              traditional: {
                Angel: "/glossary/#angel-message",
                Bad: "/glossary/#bad-harmful",
                Blasphemy: "/glossary/#blasphemy-disrespectfulness",
                Clean: "/glossary/#clean-clean",
                Confession: "/glossary/#confession-open-acknowledgement",
                "Defiled/Profane": "/glossary/#defiled-common",
                Demon: "/glossary/#demon-demon",
                Devil: "/glossary/#devil-false-accuser",
                Evil: "/glossary/#evil-hardship",
                Faith: "/glossary/#faith-trust",
                Flesh: "/glossary/#flesh-body",
                Forgiveness: "/glossary/#forgiveness-letting-go",
                "Gehenna/Hell": "/glossary/#gehenna-hinnom-valley",
                Glory: "/glossary/#glory-praiseworthiness",
                "Good -1-": "/glossary/#good-admirable",
                "Good -2-": "/glossary/#good-beneficial",
                Gospel: "/glossary/#gospel-triumphant-message",
                Grace: "/glossary/#grace-generosity",
                Heaven: "/glossary/#heaven-sky",
                "Hell/Hades": "/glossary/#hell-hades",
                Holy: "/glossary/#holy-sacred",
                Law: "/glossary/#law-torah",
                Repentance: "/glossary/#repentance-reorient-mind",
                Resurrection: "/glossary/#resurrection-reawakening",
                Righteousness: "/glossary/#righteousness-justness",
                Salvation: "/glossary/#salvation-liberation",
                Satan: "/glossary/#satan-adversary",
                Sin: "/glossary/#sin-deviation",
                Spirit: "/glossary/#spirit-life-breath",
                "Trespass/Transgression": "/glossary/#trespass-shortfall",
                Unclean: "/glossary/#unclean-unclean",
              },
              lit: {
                "The Adversary": "/glossary/#satan-adversary",
                "Appealing/Admirable": "/glossary/#good-admirable",
                "Beneficial to people": "/glossary/#good-beneficial",
                "Body/Family/Impulses": "/glossary/#flesh-body",
                Clean: "/glossary/#clean-clean",
                Demon: "/glossary/#demon-demon",
                Deviation: "/glossary/#sin-deviation",
                Disrespectfulness: "/glossary/#blasphemy-disrespectfulness",
                "False Accuser": "/glossary/#devil-false-accuser",
                Generosity: "/glossary/#grace-generosity",
                Harmful: "/glossary/#bad-harmful",
                Hardship: "/glossary/#evil-hardship",
                "The heavens/sky": "/glossary/#heaven-sky",
                "Hinnom Valley": "/glossary/#gehenna-hinnom-valley",
                Justness: "/glossary/#righteousness-justness",
                "Letting Go": "/glossary/#forgiveness-letting-go",
                Liberation: "/glossary/#salvation-liberation",
                "Life-breath/Spirit-breath": "/glossary/#spirit-life-breath",
                Messenger: "/glossary/#angel-message",
                "Open Acknowledgment":
                  "/glossary/#confession-open-acknowledgement",
                "Ordinary/unconsecrated": "/glossary/#defiled-common",
                "Place of the dead": "/glossary/#hell-hades",
                "Reawakening/Standing up":
                  "/glossary/#resurrection-reawakening",
                "Renown/Praiseworthiness": "/glossary/#glory-praiseworthiness",
                "Shortfall/Sidestep": "/glossary/#trespass-shortfall",
                "Triumphant Message": "/glossary/#gospel-triumphant-message",
                "Trust/Faithfulness": "/glossary/#faith-trust",
                Sacred: "/glossary/#holy-sacred",
                Torah: "/glossary/#law-torah",
                "Reorienting the mind": "/glossary/#repentance-reorient-mind",
                Unclean: "/glossary/#unclean-unclean",
              },
            };

            const categorySelect = document.getElementById("category-select");
            const wordSelect = document.getElementById("word-select");
            const goButton = document.getElementById("go-button");

            if (!categorySelect || !wordSelect || !goButton) return;

            wordSelect.disabled = true;
            goButton.disabled = true;

            categorySelect.addEventListener("change", () => {
              const selectedCategory = categorySelect.value;

              wordSelect.innerHTML = '<option value="">Select a Word</option>';
              wordSelect.disabled = true;
              goButton.disabled = true;

              if (selectedCategory && glossary[selectedCategory]) {
                const words = glossary[selectedCategory];
                for (const word in words) {
                  const option = document.createElement("option");
                  option.value = words[word];
                  option.textContent = word;
                  wordSelect.appendChild(option);
                }
                wordSelect.disabled = false;
              }
            });

            wordSelect.addEventListener("change", () => {
              goButton.disabled = !wordSelect.value;
            });

            goButton.addEventListener("click", () => {
              const selectedWordUrl = wordSelect.value;
              if (selectedWordUrl) window.location.href = selectedWordUrl;
            });
          });
        </script>

        <!-- ENTRIES BLOCK -->
        <section
          class="glossary-entries"
          data-pagefind-body
          data-pagefind-filter="type:glossary"
        >
          <!-- Index-only surface: just enough for search -->
          <div class="sr-only">
            <span data-pagefind-meta="title">Glossary</span>
            <span data-pagefind-meta="type">glossary</span>
            <span data-pagefind-meta="description">
              Translation glossary for key terms in the LIT.
            </span>
          </div>

          <!-- Full-bleed notch block -->
          <div class="entries-top" aria-hidden="true" data-pagefind-ignore>
          </div>

          <!-- Cream panel starts here -->
          <div class="entries-panel">
            <div class="wrap entries-wrap">
              <!-- ENTRY: ANGEL -->
              <article
                class="entry"
                id="angel-message"
                data-animate="underline"
              >
                <header class="entry-head">
                  <h2 class="entry-title" id="angel-message">
                    <!-- Index-only: English entry words -->
                    <span class="sr-only">Angel messenger</span>

                    <span class="entries-strike">
                      <strong>Angel</strong>
                    </span>

                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>

                    <!-- Greek transliteration should NOT be searchable -->
                    <em data-pagefind-ignore>angelos</em>

                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>

                    <!-- English gloss SHOULD be searchable -->
                    <span class="entries-underline"> messenger </span>
                  </h2>
                </header>

                <!-- Definition body should NOT be searchable -->
                <div class="entry-body" data-pagefind-ignore>
                  <p>
                    Whether this word is being used for a heavenly being, wind
                    and fire, a burning bush, or humans carrying a message, the
                    word <em>angelos</em>
                    means “messenger.” It refers to someone who speaks for another,
                    communicating something as an intermediary or as an agent. Even
                    when the message is from God to a human, the messenger can be
                    any number of things—people, natural phenomena, dreams, and yes,
                    even heavenly beings. Worth noting is that there is never a specific
                    kind of being named an “angel” in the Bible. Whatever kind of
                    being it is, if it is called an
                    <em>angelos</em>, it’s because it is conveying a message.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </article>

              <!-- ENTRY: BAD -->
              <article class="entry" id="bad-harmful" data-animate="underline">
                <header class="entry-head">
                  <h2 class="entry-title" id="bad-harmful">
                    <!-- Index-only: English entry words -->
                    <span class="sr-only">Bad harmful</span>

                    <span class="entries-strike">
                      <strong>Bad</strong>
                    </span>

                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>
                    <em data-pagefind-ignore>kakos</em>
                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>

                    <span class="entries-underline"> harmful </span>
                  </h2>
                </header>

                <div class="entry-body" data-pagefind-ignore>
                  <p>
                    (This word is the antonym of <em>kalos</em>. See the entry
                    for “good [1]” below.) This translation decision is more of
                    a matter of writing style and an understanding of the
                    psychology of language. (If you’re an especially nerdy type
                    and want to go on a deep dive, I recommend Steven Hayes’
                    Relational Frame Theory.) While, yes, <em>kakos</em> is always
                    used to describe something negative, the word “bad” in English
                    is problematic in that it is both too vague and carries too much
                    assumption about disobedience to rules. It’s a judgment about
                    the quality being described, not the quality itself. I have chosen
                    to translate this word based on the specific context with what
                    kind of negative quality is in view. Much of the time “harmful”
                    is an appropriate way to translate it, but a number of other ways
                    also get used.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </article>

              <!-- ENTRY: BLASPHEMY -->
              <article
                class="entry"
                id="blasphemy-disrespectfulness"
                data-animate="underline"
              >
                <header class="entry-head">
                  <h2 class="entry-title" id="blasphemy-disrespectfulness">
                    <!-- Index-only: English entry words -->
                    <span class="sr-only">Blasphemy disrespectfulness</span>

                    <span class="entries-strike">
                      <strong>Blasphemy</strong>
                    </span>

                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>
                    <em data-pagefind-ignore>blasphemia</em>
                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>

                    <span class="entries-underline"> disrespectfulness </span>
                  </h2>
                </header>

                <div class="entry-body" data-pagefind-ignore>
                  <p>
                    The English word “blasphemy” has come to mean a very
                    particular type of offense against God. However, the Greek
                    word is not nearly as specific as that. It means to speak
                    against something or someone in a way that is disrespectful
                    and causes it to be viewed with less esteem or more
                    judgmentalism. Words like “disrespect,” “slander,”
                    “defamation,” “belittling,” “insult” and others like these
                    could work. The Greek word
                    <em>blasphemia</em> appears dozens of times in the Bible, and
                    while many instances are about speaking or implying things against
                    God, many are not.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </article>

              <!-- ENTRY: CLEAN -->
              <article class="entry" id="clean-clean" data-animate="underline">
                <header class="entry-head">
                  <h2 class="entry-title" id="clean-clean">
                    <!-- Index-only: English entry words -->
                    <span class="sr-only">Clean clean</span>

                    <span class="entries-strike">
                      <strong>Clean</strong>
                    </span>

                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>
                    <em data-pagefind-ignore>katharos</em>
                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>

                    <span class="entries-underline"> clean </span>
                    <span data-pagefind-ignore
                      >(prepared for sacred purposes)</span
                    >
                  </h2>
                </header>

                <div class="entry-body" data-pagefind-ignore>
                  <p>
                    I have actually kept translating this word as “clean”
                    because I have not been satisfied with any alternatives, and
                    I don’t know that any real English equivalents exist. It is,
                    in fact, the Greek word for “clean,” but in the context of
                    the Bible and sacred Hebrew practices, it’s not what most of
                    us have been led to understand. First, it refers to the
                    specific context of religious life. It is not a synonym for
                    “good,” or the opposite of “abhorrent,” or “disgusting,” or
                    “contaminated.” It has to do with being prepared for sacred
                    purposes. The book “Hebrews” discusses the Tabernacle and
                    the priests being cleansed, not because they were sinful
                    beforehand but because they hadn’t been initiated or
                    inaugurated into their sacred roles yet. The ancient Hebrew
                    imagination had a much more expansive view of calling and
                    sacredness than modern Western thought.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </article>

              <!-- ENTRY: CONFESSION -->
              <article
                class="entry"
                id="confession-open-acknowledgement"
                data-animate="underline"
              >
                <header class="entry-head">
                  <h2 class="entry-title" id="confession-open-acknowledgement">
                    <!-- Index-only: English entry words -->
                    <span class="sr-only">Confession open acknowledgement</span>

                    <span class="entries-strike">
                      <strong>Confession</strong>
                    </span>

                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>
                    <em data-pagefind-ignore>homologia</em>
                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>

                    <span class="entries-underline">
                      open acknowledgement
                    </span>
                  </h2>
                </header>

                <div class="entry-body" data-pagefind-ignore>
                  <p>
                    This word is not inherently about admitting wrongdoing. It
                    is about speaking together something true. What is spoken
                    may very well be an open acknowledgment of participating in
                    harm, or it may be affirming the trustworthiness of Jesus.
                    It is an affirmation of the truth of something.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </article>

              <!-- ENTRY: DEFILED / PROFANE -->
              <article
                class="entry"
                id="defiled-common"
                data-animate="underline"
              >
                <header class="entry-head">
                  <h2 class="entry-title" id="defiled-common">
                    <!-- Index-only: English entry words -->
                    <span class="sr-only">Defiled Profane ordinary</span>

                    <span class="entries-strike">
                      <strong>Defiled/Profane</strong>
                    </span>

                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>
                    <em data-pagefind-ignore>koine</em>
                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>

                    <span class="entries-underline"> ordinary </span>
                    <span data-pagefind-ignore>
                      (unconsecrated, not designated for sacred purposes)
                    </span>
                  </h2>
                </header>

                <div class="entry-body" data-pagefind-ignore>
                  <p>
                    This word is often contrasted with “clean” and “holy” but
                    also often has nothing to do with that contrast. It simply
                    means “common” or “ordinary.” In fact, the type of Greek the
                    Bible is written in is called “Koine Greek” because it was
                    the dialect spoken by the common people. When the Bible uses
                    it about a religious context, it serves as the opposite of
                    the Greek word
                    <em>hagios</em> (see the entry for “holy” below). When it is contrasted
                    with “clean” or “holy,” it’s not because it’s inherently bad (or
                    anti-holy) but because it is referring to something or someone
                    not living in alignment with a sacred calling. They’re just following
                    the ordinary path that people usually take when they haven’t answered
                    God’s calling.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </article>

              <!-- ENTRY: DEMON -->
              <article class="entry" id="demon-demon" data-animate="underline">
                <header class="entry-head">
                  <h2 class="entry-title" id="demon-demon">
                    <!-- Index-only: English entry words -->
                    <span class="sr-only">Demon demon</span>

                    <span class="entries-strike">
                      <strong>Demon</strong>
                    </span>

                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>
                    <em data-pagefind-ignore>daimonion</em>
                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>

                    <span class="entries-underline"> demon </span>
                  </h2>
                </header>

                <div class="entry-body" data-pagefind-ignore>
                  <p>
                    It may be surprising to note that I have continued to
                    translate
                    <em>daimonion</em> as “demon.” There isn’t a better alternative.
                    What it has in view is almost certainly not what modern American
                    readers think of when we hear the word “demon,” those ideas are
                    formed by Medieval European folklore, not biblical teachings,
                    but it is talking about something that can’t just be dismissed
                    out of hand.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </article>

              <!-- ENTRY: DEVIL -->
              <article
                class="entry"
                id="devil-false-accuser"
                data-animate="underline"
              >
                <header class="entry-head">
                  <h2 class="entry-title" id="devil-false-accuser">
                    <!-- Index-only: English entry words -->
                    <span class="sr-only">Devil False Accuser</span>

                    <span class="entries-strike">
                      <strong>Devil</strong>
                    </span>

                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>
                    <em data-pagefind-ignore>diabolon</em>
                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>

                    <span class="entries-underline"> False Accuser </span>
                  </h2>
                </header>

                <div class="entry-body" data-pagefind-ignore>
                  <p>
                    The word “devil” isn’t really a translation. It’s a keeping
                    of the Greek word, filtered through Latin, then French, then
                    English. The word really means something like “slanderer”
                    or, more particularly, “false accuser.” There does seem to
                    be a sense of a particular False Accuser in mind, and it is
                    noteworthy that the work of diminishing someone to the label
                    of bad or wrong or evil or worthless is explicitly the work
                    of the False Accuser, not God, contrary to the doctrine of
                    Total Depravity (if you don’t know what that is, consider
                    yourself fortunate).
                  </p>
                </div>
              </article>

              <!-- ENTRY: EVIL -->
              <article
                class="entry"
                id="evil-hardship"
                data-animate="underline"
              >
                <header class="entry-head">
                  <h2 class="entry-title" id="evil-hardship">
                    <!-- Index-only: English entry words -->
                    <span class="sr-only">Evil harmful</span>

                    <span class="entries-strike">
                      <strong>Evil</strong>
                    </span>

                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>
                    <em data-pagefind-ignore>poneros</em>
                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>

                    <span class="entries-underline"> harmful </span>
                    <span data-pagefind-ignore> (oppressive, hardship) </span>
                  </h2>
                </header>

                <div class="entry-body" data-pagefind-ignore>
                  <p>
                    (This word is the antonym of <em>agathos</em>. See the entry
                    for “good [2]” below.) The word “evil” has come to mean
                    something along the lines of a malicious and hostile person
                    who seeks their own gain or even takes pleasure in the pain
                    of others. A person who fits that description could possibly
                    be considered to fit the definition of <em>poneros</em>, but
                    that’s not specifically what it means. At its core, it’s
                    about anything that causes hardship, especially oppressive
                    or disastrous hardship. A tornado would fit this
                    description. An occupying army would fit this description.
                    It’s about the hardship caused for people, not the wicked
                    desires that make something
                    <em>poneros</em>. The person or community who makes life
                    harder for others, who treats others as objects for one’s
                    own gain or benefit, is <em>poneros</em>
                    (as an adjective). The effects of that posture to others, the
                    impacts on the other people, could also be called <em
                      >poneros</em
                    > (as a noun).
                  </p>
                </div>
              </article>

              <!-- ENTRY: FAITH -->
              <article class="entry" id="faith-trust" data-animate="underline">
                <header class="entry-head">
                  <h2 class="entry-title" id="faith-trust">
                    <!-- Index-only: split slash into tokens -->
                    <span class="sr-only">Faith trust faithfulness</span>

                    <span class="entries-strike">
                      <strong>Faith</strong>
                    </span>

                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>
                    <em data-pagefind-ignore>pistis</em>
                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>

                    <span class="entries-underline">
                      trust<span class="pf-slash-space"> </span>/<span
                        class="pf-slash-space"
                      >
                      </span>faithfulness
                    </span>
                  </h2>
                </header>

                <div class="entry-body" data-pagefind-ignore>
                  <p>
                    This word is complex. It is traditionally translated as
                    “faith” or “belief” or “faithfulness” based on context. The
                    first two have become too misconstrued to be useful anymore.
                    The heart of the word is a reciprocal relationship between
                    trust and faithfulness. It can lean on the sense of a bond
                    of trust toward a person or way of being that a person
                    teaches in some places, and it can lean on the trusting
                    response to that person or that way of being that emulates
                    it. Trust leads to faithfulness and faithfulness leads to
                    trust. There is a committedness involved that chooses to be
                    faithful because of trusting the source of encouragement to
                    stick to the path even when hoped-for outcomes are still in
                    the distant future.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </article>

              <!-- ENTRY: FLESH -->
              <article class="entry" id="flesh-body" data-animate="underline">
                <header class="entry-head">
                  <h2 class="entry-title" id="flesh-body">
                    <!-- Index-only: include split tokens so searches for either match -->
                    <span class="sr-only"
                      >Flesh self-preservation self preservation family</span
                    >

                    <span class="entries-strike">
                      <strong>Flesh</strong>
                    </span>

                    <span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;–&nbsp;</span>
                    <em data-pagefind-ignore>sarx</em>
